The house of the bones continues to fascinate after 100 years. They observe the interiors of Gaudí
The roof looks like the lome of a prehistoric pond, the stairs remind the column of a dinosaur and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, of the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its shape similar to a skeleton, the locals seized "the house of the bones".
Its organic shapes, its striking colors, the innovative use of the stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a façade that resembles the smoothly curved scales and omnipresent lines, all of which is typical of the secession of Antoni Gaudí.
