Serpentea and the twisting of the shapes continue to surprise us also inside.
The wafted wood copies the frames of the windows, the beams, the decorations of the doors, the mirrors and the letters.
The Casa Batlló, located in the Eixample neighborhood in the 43rd of the lively commercial street of Passeig de Gràcia, emerged from the remodeling of a house in 1877 by architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the industrial rich Josep Batlló, initially insisted on breaking down the previous building and starting at zero, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea of a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Batlló House, consisting of several apartments, did not design it alone, Antoni Gaudí.
The architect Josep María Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in its plans of the project there were ornaments for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the mosaics used in the façade.
In the façade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of Casa Batlló was the beginning of Jujol's successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of the Milá House and Güell Park in Gaudí, where there are other parts of it.
Because of its organic form, the locals soon after its completion seized "the house of the bones".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows, began to call it "the house of the ruins".
It is also said that, above construction, the sword of San Jorge, patron of Catalonia appears.
Other sculptural elements of the building hide religious motives.
Gaudí designed in the house a unique system for central heating times with ventilation respirators and typical fireplaces.
It may be strange to have a forty-five degree inclination.
During the construction, Gaudí did not comply at all with the building standards of the time and was not influenced by them.
Even so, the construction was granted the permit from the beginning, although it clearly showed that the planned reconstruction data were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the town was so affected by the result that it was requested to be corrected.
For example, he was upset that the construction included columns even to the public side.
The arrangements were never made, rather than the contrary: only fifteen days after the city's request, Joseph Batlló requested permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
The owner himself was installed on the lower floors.
In the gallery of the second floor there were the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The house, with six floors, is completely crossed by a staircase that leads to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform were to break all right angles and lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the rooms and a larger group can be communicated in this way without problems, without giving up the privacy required for more intimate conversations.
The house, with the reconstruction of Gaudí, not only obtained a new façade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white blues and blues that cover the inner courtyard and tragaluces.
The game with both colors brings the maximum light on all the floors of the house.
It was simply based on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which otherwise absorb the sun's rays.
Anyone can visit the Batlló House, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and recharged apartment available to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits, they confirmed, or discovered, that it was a very beneficial business and extended the visits to the common area and to the bush, including the roof terrace.
