More and more parents use tracking devices to control their children
The fear of children keeps more and more people thinking about controlling them by GPS.
The system, originally designed to track vehicles, can also follow the movement of people and contribute so, for example, in the event of the disappearance of the nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
The device currently has the approximate size of a lockbox, but it will soon be reduced to the size of a clock.
Many people were afraid of the missing Anička and began to inform about the means available to protect their children better.
Even at the cost of attacking your privacy.
"We all try to tell ourselves that it is not about spying, but about another way to reduce the possibility of a tragedy," says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the providers of tracking devices in the Czech market.
"I recognize that, in certain cases, such devices can be abused, for example if they are put into someone's pocket without their knowledge, but we have not yet met with such cases."
"Most customers actually buy it for security reasons," Pilin added.
In their view, children should always know what "cajita" is and how it is used in an emergency.
Children's psychologist Dana Bočkova warns about the fact that if the child doesn't want to take it, he'll just pull it off.
"Even younger children show great creativity at the time of intentionally losing certain things if they want to avoid controlling them."
"In the past, parents relied heavily on mobile phones, but these could be turned off as easily as the tracking device," Bočkova says.
In his view, it is questionable if such a device is really useful in the event of an attack.
"If it is a prepared kidnapping, the author will practically always check if the child carries some kind of electronic device that can unveil his location."
"Now it's the phone."
"As the use of tracking devices is expanding, you will also search for them, as your sale will undoubtedly be made with much publicity."
"In such cases, criminals always go a step ahead of the police," says psychologist.
However, it adds that such devices can help in the case of an improvised attack of a pedophile.
According to Robert Čech of the RC Monitoring company, which provides tracking services for both vehicles and persons, even if, after an attack, the tracking device is immediately destroyed, its presence can serve as aid.
"The device can be configured to send the position regularly after a certain period."
"If damage occurs, at least it will facilitate the last position of the person concerned."
"The most expensive devices are integrated with a tilting meter, so if the person just unwinds and remains mobile, the device will immediately issue a warning with the position in question," says Čech.
In your opinion, a service of this type can even be obtained with intelligent mobile phones with navigation, where only a special software should be installed.
