Cockell wasn't part of the research team.
"This work is novel because it demonstrates the substitution of one element by another in the basic biochemical and biochemical structure," Cockell added.
The discovery was not carried out by accident.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of the NASA Institute of Astrobiology, who conducted the study, focused on the Mono Lake because she has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are similar from a chemical point of view, so he speculated that a microbe exposed to both could replace each other.
"Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is similar to that of phosphorus."
"As a result, it may be difficult for agencies to differentiate them."
"However, arsenic is quite different than so that it does not work as well as phosphorus, so it comes in and, by some means, appellates biochemical machinery," Anbar explains.
The researchers collected the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed them to increasing arsenic concentrations, to which they were adapted and used to grow.
