The National Administration for Aeronautics and Space (NASA) of the United States will introduce tomorrow, Thursday, an astrobiological discovery that could prove the theory that there is an extraterrestrial life.
The discovery will be presented in a press conference Thursday morning at 13:00 in the headquarters of NASA in Washington by experts in astrobiology, a science described as studying the origin, evolution, distribution and future of life in the Universe.
When the press was quoted, NASA assured that it would present "a finding that would impact on the search for extraterrestrial life", resulting in speculation of experts from other countries.
The discovery could demonstrate the theory that there are creatures in our pair and in hostile environments that were thought to be uninhabitable, and would put on the table the possibility that they would become intelligent beings like humans if they improved the conditions in which they live.
This seems to be a microbe found at the bottom of the Mono Lake in the Yosemite National Park, California, where it lives in an environment that was too poisonous for any form of life, as the lake is rich in arsenic.
In some ways, the creature uses arsenic as a way of survival and this capacity increases the possibility that similar life could exist on other planets, which do not have our favorable atmosphere.
According to astrobiologists, if these organisms use arsenic in their metabolism, it will be shown that "there is another way of life, a second way of life, different from what we know."
The space agency will make known the true scope of the findings at the press conference on Thursday morning.
The conference will be attended by geobiologist Pamela Conrad, who studies the possibility of life in Mars; and biologist Steven Benner, one of the scientists studying Titan (the largest moon in Saturn), from the perspective that his chemistry is similar to that of Earth.
