A Global Plan to Renewal of Lighting
Yesterday, in Cancún, the United Nations has proposed a plan for the renewal of domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in hundreds of countries to reduce greenhouse gas (GEI) to an amount that is practically equivalent to a third of the additional reduction that needs to be implemented to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is reflected in the whole of major concrete projects that the United Nations expects to adopt in Cancún to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments in industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if incandescent bombs, which still monopolies between 50 and 70% of the market, were replaced by fluo-compact bombs or, better still, electroluminescent diodes (DEL or LED) bombs, much of the 1,800 million tons (Gt) of GI emitted on the planet would be avoided to illuminate humans.
Lighting is responsible for 8 per cent of global emissions.
It is equivalent to 70% of emissions from the planetary motor park.
In Copenhagen, last year, large countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans that should reduce GHG global emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, a further 5 Gt of this amount should be reduced to stabilize, before 2020, the rise in temperatures in two centigrades to prevent it from being uncontrollable.
In the incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is released in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5%, produces light.
In the case of fluo-compact pumps, energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new LED pumps, energy consumption is reduced twice more.
Fluocompact pumps last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bombs, such as those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week (a company that has also participated in the UN study), have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bomb, which allows us to make an idea of the savings that can be achieved with the replacement plan that would be applied in one hundred countries.
These new bombs can also work with resustants and emit very little heat.
Above all, they don't contain any mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations regarding fluo-compact pumps, since they contain mercury and should be eliminated as hazardous wastes, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers provide instructions.
However, the report indicates that the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the fluo-compact pumps, but the coal thermal power plants, which emit a large amount of mercury to produce the electricity that melts with incandescent bombs.
Only in the United States, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the benefits of this international programme to each country.
For example, Indonesia would thus save billions of dollars a year in electricity and eight million tons of CO2, i.e. the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants whose construction would cost 2,500 million.
